{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e12e3466-1844-4118-99e1-a5629935de60","content":"Yes, both approaches are **correct and still valid** for .NET MAUI on .NET 10.\n\n**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This iOS platform-specific tells the page to respect safe area insets (notch, Dynamic Island, home indicator). You'll need the namespace:\n\n```xml\nxmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"`** — This lets individual layouts extend *into* the unsafe area (e.g., for a full-bleed background image), even when the page has `UseSafeArea` enabled.\n\n**Typical pattern:**\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage ...\n    xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n    ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n\n    <Grid IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\">\n        <Image Source=\"background.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n        <!-- Content here stays within safe area via inner layout -->\n    </Grid>\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nThis gives you a background that bleeds edge-to-edge while keeping interactive content safely away from the notch/Dynamic Island. Your tutorial's guidance is solid.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"63b6f5c6-382a-441b-b54d-1e143fb201ae","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - a property on Grid\n\nLet me think about what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs and whether these are correct for .NET 10.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the safe area handling has evolved. Let me recall:\n\n- In earlier Xamarin.Forms / early MAUI, there was `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` as a platform-specific.\n\n\n- The approach has shifted in more recent MAUI versions, and I need to verify what's actually available in .NET 10. The `IgnoreSafeArea` property exists on layouts to let specific views extend beyond the safe area, but I should be careful about whether these exact APIs are the current recommended approach or if they've been superseded. I'm setting up the iOS namespace for platform-specific properties and confirming that both `UseSafeArea` and `IgnoreSafeArea` should work in .NET MAUI on .NET 10, though I want to be careful about the exact API surface since these have evolved over time.","outputTokens":1140,"requestId":"9BC4:11AB75:6275129:6DBDAC7:69EC11A6"},"id":"236aa841-b3e6-4c44-a234-ca0930a73eac","timestamp":"2026-04-25T00:58:35.433Z","parentId":"d0c09fb4-5c09-4307-ab93-a60c055ae3d1"}
